1 Introduction

This is a comprehensive Exploratory Data Analysis for the mobile app data. I will be using ggplot2 and the tidyverse tools to study and visualize the structures in the data.

The data comes in 4 different CSV files and includes 5 keys:
Files:
1) activity_data - monthly aggregated data of minutes spent on an app by a device
2) app_publisher - publisher to app_name mapping
3) demo_info - demographic information of a device
4) additional_activity_data - activity data collected from additional users but without device level information
Keys:
app_name - App Name
publisher - Creator/Owner of the App. A Publisher can have multiple apps
device_id - unique id for a smartphone user
gender_id - 1 is Male ; 2 is Female
minutes - Time spent (in minutes) in an entire month

1.1 Assumption

In order to ensure the accuracy of the analysis, the following assumptions are made:
1. The percentage of female and male in the overall population are both 50%.
2. Both male and female have similar consumption power and merchants have the same probability of gaining profit from men and women.
3. Consumers time to use APP is positively correlated with the probability of seeing an advertisement and making a purchase.

2.3 Dealing with missing values in activity_data

By observing the dataset, we find that the average active minutes for each app is significantly different from each other and for 748 out of 22440 activities (3.3%), the active minutes are missing.
So we choose to use the average active minute of each app replace all NA data.

# group by APP name
a<-aggregate(x = activity_data$minutes,                # Specify data column
          by = list(activity_data$app_name),              # Specify group indicator
          FUN = mean) # Specify function (i.e. mean)
a

We use the average active minute of each app to replace all NA data.

# using dplyr library to replace NAs with the average minutes of the APP groups
activity_data%>%
     group_by(app_name) %>% 
      mutate(minutes = ifelse(is.na(minutes), mean(minutes, na.rm = TRUE), minutes))->activity_data

Inspect if all NAs were successfully replaced.

#inspect: all NAs are successfully replaced
any(is.na(activity_data)) # are there any NAs?
## [1] FALSE

In demo_info, 98 out of 2774 (3.5%) users gender data are missing. Since the missing gender data is binomial and takes only 3.5%, we will simply remove the rows that contain missing data and analyze with the remaining 96.5% gender data.

Create subsets of data and only keep complete cases.

# remove NA rows

2.5 Handling Outliers and Identify Errors

Its important to identify outliers because they arent representative of the rest of the population. They also could be flat-out incorrect; the more atypical the value, the more likely it could be a mistake in the data.

Now we want to figure out if there are any suspicious values for active minutes form the active_data, including values that are way too low or way too high.

Steps:

  • Draw a boxplot before removing outliers with ggplot2
  • Eliminate all outliers using the IQR function and obtain a clean dataset
  • Draw a boxplot after removing outliers with ggplot2

2.4.1 Create a boxplot before removing outliers.

From the graph, the outlier is so large and so different from the majority that the boxplot does not even look like a box.

# Create a boxplot.
fill <- "#4271AE"
line <- "#1F3552"
 ggplot(activity_data, aes(x = "", y = minutes)) +
        geom_boxplot(fill = fill, colour = line, alpha = 0.7) +
        scale_y_continuous(name = "Minutes") + theme_bw()

        ggtitle("Box plot: Activity data before removing outliers")
## $title
## [1] "Box plot: Activity data before removing outliers"
## 
## attr(,"class")
## [1] "labels"

2.4.2 Eliminate all outliers

Ill be using the quantile() function to find the 25th and the 75th percentile of the dataset, and the IQR() function which elegantly gives me the difference of the 75th and 25th percentiles.
It may be noted here that the quantile() function only takes in numerical vectors as inputs whereas activity_data is a data frame. I, therefore, specified a relevant column by adding $minutes, this passes only the minutes column as a numerical vector. The IQR function also requires numerical vectors and therefore arguments are passed in the same way.

Q<-quantile(activity_data$minutes,probs=c(0.25,0.75),na.rm=FALSE)
iqr <- IQR(activity_data$minutes)
up <-  Q[2]+1.5*iqr # Upper Range  
low<- Q[1]-1.5*iqr # Lower Range
activity_clean<- subset(activity_data, activity_data$minutes > (Q[1] - 1.5*iqr) & activity_data$minutes  < (Q[2]+1.5*iqr))

2.4.3 Create a boxplot after removing outliers and glimpse the clean activity dataset

From the boxplots, we know that before removing outliers, the minutes range from 0 to 14000. This range is too large and some bad data may influence the accuracy. After removing outliers, we narrow down the minutes data to range (0, 600), which is significantly smaller. And we do not lose a lot of data the remaining data counts for 85.5% of the original data.

fill <- "#4271AE"
line <- "#1F3552"
 ggplot(activity_clean, aes(x = "", y = minutes)) +
        geom_boxplot(fill = fill, colour = line, alpha = 0.7) +
        scale_y_continuous(name = "Minutes") + theme_bw()+
        ggtitle("Box plot: Activity data after removing outliers")

# glimpse cleaned activity_data

3 Publisher Analysis: Select Best Publishers

In this part, we provide insights on selecting the best publishers and apps for the advertisers to boost marketing compaign.

We first select three top performing publishers by analyzing the total active time, the average active time and the number of distinct users. Then we look into the detail apps of these three publishers and evaluate the performance of the apps.

3.2 Select Top Three Publishers

3.2.1 Summarize Key Insights

activity_demo_publisher%>%
  group_by(Publisher)%>%
  summarise(total_minutes=round(sum(minutes),digits = 2),
            average_minutes_per_activity=round(mean(minutes),digits = 2),
            number_of_activities=n(),
            distinct_users=n_distinct(device_id),
            median=median(minutes))%>%
arrange(desc(total_minutes))%>%
 arrange(desc(total_minutes)) -> Publisher_analysis
Publisher_analysis

3.2.2 Total Active Time Analysis

Namely, the total active time of Facebook is 713801.9 minutes and is 386% the average active time; and total active time of Google Site is 490010.15 minutes and is 265% the average active time.

Comprehensively considering the analysis of the above three aspects, Facebook is the best performing publisher with the total active time 286% higher than the industry average active time; distincter users 78% higher than the average and average active time 182 minutes 133% higher than the average.

The second top performing publisher is Google Site with the total active time 165% higher than the industry average active time; distincter users 108% higher than the average and average active time 67 minutes 14% lower than the industry average.

The third best publisher is Snapchat. The average active time of snapchat is 49% higher than industry average, which indicates the users stickness is high. And snapchat has the total active time in the third place(25% lower than industrial average) and distinct users in the fourth place(8% lower than average).

4 Demographic Feature Analysis Gender Analysis

4.1 Remove Demographic Bias

We discover gender bias exists in the dataset from the pie chart. The percentage of male and female should be around 50%, however, 62% data from the demo_info dataset were labeled female while 38% male.

activity_demo_publisher%>%
  group_by(gender_id)%>%
  summarise(distinct_users=n_distinct(device_id),
            percentage=percent(n_distinct(device_id)/2676),
            number_of_activities=n()) -> Only_Gender
# Create a basic pie chart
ggplot(Only_Gender, aes(x="", y=distinct_users, fill=gender_id)) + geom_bar(stat="identity", width=1)+ coord_polar("y", start=0) + geom_text(aes(label = paste0(percentage)), position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5)) +  scale_fill_brewer()  + labs(x = NULL, y = NULL, fill = NULL, title = "Demographic - Gender percentage") + theme_classic() + theme(axis.line = element_blank(),
          axis.text = element_blank(),
          axis.ticks = element_blank(),
          plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, color = "#666666"))

glimpse(Only_Gender)
## Observations: 2
## Variables: 4
## $ gender_id            <chr> "Female", "Male"
## $ distinct_users       <int> 1657, 1019
## $ percentage           <chr> "62%", "38%"
## $ number_of_activities <int> 11728, 6802

Since the demo_info dataset contains 1657 female and 1019 male, the methodology to solve the demographic bias is to randomly select 638 female and delete the selected data. In this way, we keep 1019 female and 1019 male in the dataset, and the percentage of both group are 50%.

demo_info%>%
  filter(gender_id==2)->female
female<- female[-sample(nrow(female), 638), ] ##randomly sampling
demo_info%>%
filter(gender_id==1)->male
library(gtools)
rbind(male,female)->demo1 ## save new dataset
demo1%>%
group_by(gender_id)%>%
  summarise(distinct_users=n_distinct(device_id) ) ##the count of both gender are equal

4.3 Gender Analysis

4.3.1 Total Active Time Analysis

ggplot(Gender_analysis, aes(x=reorder(Publisher, -total_minutes), y=round(total_minutes,0), fill=reorder(gender_id, -total_minutes))) + 
   geom_bar(stat="identity", position=position_dodge()) + scale_fill_brewer(palette="Paired","Gender")+
  theme_minimal()+xlab("Publisher")+ylab("Total Minutes")+ggtitle("Total Minutes of Each Publisher")

4.3.3 Average Active Time Analysis

ggplot(Gender_analysis, aes(x=reorder(Publisher, -average_minutes_per_activity), y=average_minutes_per_activity, fill=reorder(gender_id, -average_minutes_per_activity))) +

Key insights:

  • Overall, there is no big difference in the total active time, average active time and distinctive between men and women.
  • Snapchat have slightly more male users.
  • Pinterest have more female users.
